`dnspython` is what you want. I spent 5 minutes working on it a couple of weeks ago but abandoned my efforts because I have no time for it, but I did identify some ... complications.

My (non-functional) stub is:

```python
import logging
import dns.update

from .base import Provider as BaseProvider

logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)

def ProviderParser(subparser):
    subparser.description = '''
        The RFC2136 provider requires the RFC2136 server, TSIG key name and TSIG key secret.'''
    subparser.add_argument('--auth-username', help='The TSIG Key Name')
    subparser.add_argument('--auth-token', help='The TSIG Key Secret')
    subparser.add_argument('--auth-server', help='The RFC2136 server')

class Provider(BaseProvider):

    def __init__(self, options, engine_overrides=None):
        super(Provider, self).__init__(options, engine_overrides)

        if not self.options['auth_username']:
            raise Exception('Error, TSIG Key Name is not defined')
        if not self.options['auth_token']:
            raise Exception('Error, TSIG Key Secret is not defined')
        if not self.options['auth_server']:
            raise Exception('Error, RFC2136 Server is not defined')

    def authenticate(self):
        self.keyring = dns.tsigkeyring.from_text({
            self.options['auth_username']: self.options['auth_token']
        })
    
    def create_record(self, type, name, content):
        ttl = self.options['ttl']
        if not ttl:
            ttl = 21600

        update = dns.update.Update(self.options['domain'], keyring=self.keyring)
        update.add(self._relative_name(name), ttl, content)

        response = dns.query.tcp(update, self.options['auth_server'])
        logger.debug('create_record: %s', response)

        return True

    def list_records(self, type=None, name=None, content=None):
        records = []

        logger.debug('list_records: %s', records)
        return records

    def update_record(self, identifier, type=None, name=None, content=None):
        ttl = self.options['ttl']
        if not ttl:
            ttl = 21600

        update = dns.update.Update(self.options['domain'], keyring=self.keyring)
        return True

    def delete_record(self, identifier=None, type=None, name=None, content=None):
        return True
```

and you can take a look at [Certbot's RFC2136 implementation](https://github.com/certbot/certbot/blob/master/certbot-dns-rfc2136/certbot_dns_rfc2136/dns_rfc2136.py) for an example of that library is meant to be used.

Here's the latest on group tasks. The short version is that you can enter (fuzzy parsed) date-times for `&s` in jobs but they will be stored internally as timedeltas relative to the `@s` entry for the task group.

### Example

    - sequential task group @s 6/10 12p @a 1d @b 3
    @j First  &s 6/3 9a
    @j Second &s 6/5 10a
    @j Third

or, equivalently, as:

    - sequential task group @s 6/10 12p @a 1d @b 3
    @j First  &s 6/3 9a  &i 1
    @j Second &s 6/5 10a &i 2 &p 1
    @j Third  &i 3 &p 2

In the absence of `&i id` and `&p prereqs` entries, etm would generate them implicitly so, internally, these would be the same to etm.  Either way, there would be no prereqs for *First*, *First* would be the only prereq for *Second* and *Second* would be the only prereq for *Third*. For more complicated, non-sequential structures, it would be necessary, of course, to add the `&i` and `&p` elements explicitly.

**Treatment of `@s`, `@a`, `@b`, `&s`, `&a` and `&b` elements**

* For date-only and date-time items, `@s` is required and becomes the default for `&s` in each task. Similarly, if given, `@a` and `@b` become the defaults for `&a` and `&b`, respectively, in each task.
* Fuzzy parsing including relative datetimes is allowed for both `@s` and `&s`. In the example above, `@s` could, on 2016-05-30, equivalently have been entered as `@s +10 12p`.
* If `&s` is given, it is stored internally as a timedelta relative to `@s`. The default when `&s` is omitted is `0m`. In the example above, `&s` for *First*  would parse as 2016-06-03 09:00am but, on 2016-05-30, could equivalently have been entered as `&s +3 9a`. In either case it would be stored internally as `7d3h`, i.e., as 7 days and 3 hours before 2016-06-10 12:00pm.
* Alerts and beginbys **are only active for available jobs**, i.e., jobs without unfinished prerequisites. In the example above, only *First* would initially be available, its `&a` entry would default to `1d` and would thus set an alert for *First* at `1d + 7d3h = 8d3h` before 2016-06-10 12:00pm or at 2016-06-02 09:00am. Similarly, `&b` would default to `3` in *First* and would set a beginby for *First* beginning at 2016-06-01 12:00am.

