> Not really, it's just that if you call it like that, Jedi will basically call py__iter__. __iter__ is something you have defined yourself:
Ah, sure, that's wrong anyways. Before solving the tuple-case, how can I fix this one (it should return an undefined number of items of type `indextypes[0]`)?

```
class Iterable(abc.Iterable):
    def __iter__(self):
        while True:
            yield indextypes[0]()
```
Doesn't seem to do the trick. 

Neither does
```
    class Iterable(abc.Iterable):
        def __iter__(self):
            class Iter:
                def __next__(self):
                    return indextypes[0]()
            return Iter()
```

Both do the same as the current code, only returning the first item

```
class Iterable(abc.Iterable):
    def __iter__(self):
        yield indextypes[0]()
        yield indextypes[0]()
```
Correctly assigns the first two, no more.... (as expected)

>You're right. But I would not go too far away from mypy's way of doing things. Mypy evals those strings (which means that all the operations (additions and so on) are performed. Of course it's ok to do it like you did, but in the longterm I would probably like to switch, simply because it's more complicated the way we're doing it now. But let's leave it for now.

I will try to think a bit more about it. There is more different behaviour between the two approaches:

- Using a different typehinting scheme (i.e. docstring) with the `typing` module, I think the correct behaviour should be to not resolve FRs (which it doesn't in the current code, it did in the code where the FRs where fixed in the typing module). There is no reason to use FRs in docstrings. Then again, there is no reason not to support it, it will not break any other behaviour. So not much of an argument

- Using FR with one's own typing module should work, I think. However I'm really trying to see if any such typing module would just be a contrived example that nobody would actually ever make. So not too sure this is a good argument either.

So I tend to agree with you that perhaps the best course of action for now it to revert 10f5e1, since that code is easier, and actually seems to better follow the spirit (although not the letter) of pep0484.

In the coming weeks I should have some more time to spend on this, hopefully we can get this stuff to merge soon. Just out of curiosity, how mature do you think the linter-branch currently is? Do you feel it's on par with the current master/stable?

