Thanks @aseemw for the very detailed answer. There is however something I still don't understand which seems like a bug.

When I run a prediction with an input array of dimensions `(1, 20, 8000)` the output is an array of dimensions `(2000, 1025)`. If a 3D array is interpreted as `CHW` and the input shape to my model should be a 1D array:

```
input {
  name: "input1"
  type {
    multiArrayType {
      shape: 8000
      dataType: DOUBLE
    }
  }
}
output {
  name: "output1"
  type {
    multiArrayType {
      shape: 1025
      dataType: DOUBLE
    }
  }
}
```

Then why doesn't the predict method raise an exception when I use a 3D array as input? 

In fact if I reshape my input (e.g to (1,40,4000) I get the following exception when running a prediction:

```
RuntimeError: {
    NSLocalizedDescription = "Input feature input1 was presented as a batch  (length 40) of sequences (length 1) of vectors of length 4000, but the model expects vectors of length 8000.";
}
```

Which is particularly confusing if as you say a 3D input is needed for a batch.

@tdesvenain Yeah, if you read my explanation in https://github.com/plone/mockup/pull/832#issuecomment-369113718 you can see at the bottom I mentioned about adding such a line in the tests, however that would only work when you call the pattern manually, ie. ```new TinyMCE($el);``` however, there are several other tests where the "pat-tinymce" class is used and then ```registry.scan($el);``` is called.

After banging my head for several hours around this, I wouldn't like to manually add ```tinymce.tiny.initialized = true; ```... That flag should be set as part of the tinymce init code, and as far as I understand, it has to do with the fact that tinymce is created asynchronously. I think the proper way around this would be for the tinymce tests to properly wait until the widget is created... I don't know how to do that.

This is why it works fine in the browser, but not in the tests...

