@stefanv it's there for a good reason, which is that people might want to use whatever fancy labelling algorithm they have and then remove the small resulting objects — which may be discontiguous, or not separated by 0s. It's also much more efficient not to re-run the labelling if it's already been done.

When there are just 0 and 1 as labels, we could detect it as a binary image — which we already do, see the warning you raised! It even tells you to convert your image to bool. Back in the day, automatically converting it was seen as too much magic. I myself like magic so would be ok with changing it.

Josh might argue that you don't want the behaviour to magically change with only one label, because you might be processing a series of images, and one of them will happen to have a single label and you want to treat it as such. There would be no way whatsoever for users to do a `remove_small_objects` on an image with a single label if we change the behaviour.

