A straightforward apporach would be to only do the check for `is_iterable_but_not_string` and serialize each of the value's elements with the inner field's `_serialize` method.

```python
    def _serialize(self, value, attr, obj):
        if value is None:
            return self.default
        if utils.is_iterable_but_not_string(value):
            return [self.container._serialize(each, attr, obj) for each in value]
        else:
            return [self.container.serialize(attr, obj)]
```

I believe this meets all the cases described above.

@bioinformed Thanks for the extra test case (I overlooked it initially).

I've been looking into this, with partial success. It's possible to infer the install location of pysam, and then to add a second rpath for this path in `cy_build_ext`. This is sufficient to make the test pass without having to set LD_LIBRARY_PATH. This is quite easy to do.

However, this only works if the "secondary package" (i.e. the one that tries to make use of pysam) is built on the same machine that has pysam installed. Consider e.g. the example where someone has pysam installed via `python setup.py develop` and installs an pre-built wheel containing a secondary package depending on pysam. This package will have the pysam paths built in for the machine where the wheel was built, and these will probably not match the install location of pysam on the user's machine. I'm not sure this scenario was supported with the pre-#489 implementation, though.

My recommendation at this stage would be to add a second rpath to `cy_build_ext` with the install location for pysam. This will fix the situation for people that install secondary packages locally (either via `develop`/`install`, or by building a wheel on their machine and then installing it). For the case where this is not sufficient, I would admit defeat and advise users to set `LD_LIBRARY_PATH` (or tell them to `import pysam` before using any Cython modules that cimport from pysam).

@AndreasHeger @bioinformed What do you think? I write all of this without knowing the full gamut of linking use cases, so I'm perfectly OK if you decide to go with the old, pre-#489 way of linking.

